        "markerKey": "web-extension-islam-s-corrective-tradition-madhhab-al-tahqiq-the-school-of-verification:web-extension:54",
        "origin": "web-extension",
        "content": "<p> <strong>Al-Shaykh Aḥmad al-Sirhindī</strong> (d. 1034/1624) or, more fully, al-Shaykh Aḥmad ibn ‘Abd-al-Aḥad al-Fārūqī al-Sirhindī, hailed from Sindh in modern-day Pakistan but died and was buried in what is now Indian Punjab. He was an Islamic Scholar of India, a noted Ḥanafi Jurist, and a Spiritual Master in the Naqshabandī Sufi Order. Al-Shaykh Aḥmad al-Sirhindī made significant contributions to Sufi Epistemology and practice. He is known for his opposition to certain opinions and positions of the Mughal emperor Akbar (d. <strong>1013</strong>/1605). Many of the Naqshabandī Sufi sub-Orders today trace their Spiritual lineage back to al-Shaykh Aḥmad al-Sirhindī. He studied in the village of Sailkot in Punjab, which had become an Intellectual center at that time, under the direction of Mullā ‘Abd-al-Ḥakīm al-Siālkūtī (d. 1067/1657). In addition to the<em> Sharī‘a </em>Sciences, al-Shaykh Aḥmad al-Sirhindī studied the Qur’ān, <em>Ḥadīth</em>, the Prophet’s biography, history, Logic, Divinity, Metaphysics, and Philosophy. He died and was buried in Sirhind with Lahore Subah of the Mughal Empire, which is today in India and not far from the Pakistani border. </p>",
